Only by sharing a problem with the man or being dependent can Laura be recognised without becoming an additional burden for the man.
Independence Out of the fear of becoming dependent on the man, Laura decides not to settle in one of the ethnic Albanian womencentres, but she decides to return to her mother. In this way, Laura pursues a somewhat different course: growth from within the family. Whereas Sandra uses the womencentre in tandem with expanding from within the family, Laura reduces the influence of her parents on her life and this way follows an independent course. On the website of the Latvian centre Zinas.net one reads a similar way of dealing with one’s parents in women’s centres. This outlook on women’s centres is related to the dynamics of self-determination. Britain and Letherby36 show that gender-restricting norms do still exist but it is difficult to put oneself on the market without being subject to those modern social norms in one way or another. Consequently, this developing way of life without norms relies on shared resources and this can lead to looking for a place to live where this development can occur. The conclusion was that sharing resources with homesweethomes was not only a means of resistance to gender norms such as being a wife or mother but also the only way of sharing resources between a network.
